[[File:Sir James Black Baillie.jpg|alt=A sitting portrait black and white photograph of the then 59-year-old Sir James Black Baillie in 1931.|thumb|Sir James Black Baillie (1872-1940), Vice-chancellor of [[University of Leeds]]]]
'''Sir James Black Baillie''', {{post-nominals|country=GBR|OBE}} (24 October 1872 &ndash; 9 June 1940) was a British [[moral philosopher]] and Vice-Chancellor of the [[University of Leeds]].  He wrote the first significant translation of [[Hegel]]'s "Phenomenology of Mind." He is said to be the model for the character Sir John Evans in the novel ''The Weight of the Evidence'' (1944) by [[Michael Innes]].<ref name=ODNB>[[Oxford Dictionary of National Biography]] accessed 25 July 2009</ref>

==Life==
Baillie was born in West Mill, Cortachy, [[Forfarshire]] and studied  at the [[University of Edinburgh]], where he gained a PhD in 1899 on "The growth of Hegel's logic"<ref>{{Cite thesis |last=Baillie |first=James Black |date=1899 |title=Growth of Hegel's logic |url=http://hdl.handle.net/1842/23692 |language=en |publisher=University of Edinburgh}}</ref> and [[Trinity College, Cambridge]].<ref>{{acad|id=BLY897JB|name=Baillie, James Black}}</ref>  He lectured in philosophy at [[University of Dundee|University College, Dundee]], and in August 1902 was appointed Professor of Moral Philosophy at the [[University of Aberdeen]].<ref>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Court Circular |day_of_week=Friday |date=1 August 1902 |page_number=7 |issue=36835| }}</ref><ref>{{London Gazette|issue=27469 |page=5604 |date=29 August 1902}}</ref> In 1906 he married Helena May James: they had no children.<ref name=ODNB/>

During the [[First World War]] he was in the intelligence division of the [[British Admiralty]].  After public service posts he became Vice-Chancellor of the University of Leeds from 1924 to his retirement in 1938.  He died of [[prostate cancer]] in [[Weybridge]].<ref name=ODNB/>

==Honours==
He was appointed an Officer of the [[Order of the British Empire]] in the [[1919 New Year Honours]],<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=31114 |supp=y |page=453|date= 8 January 1919}}</ref> made a Knight Commander of the [[Order of the Crown of Italy]] following a meeting with Italian leader [[Benito Mussolini]]<ref name=ODNB/> and received a UK knighthood in 1931.<ref name=LonGaz>[http://www.london-gazette.co.uk/issues/33722/supplements/3623 London Gazette] 2 June 1931</ref>

